{"parse":{"title":"Sharawadji effect","pageid":51856549,"revid":859331361,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>The <b>sharawadji effect</b>, not to be confused with <a href=\"/wiki/Sharawadgi\" title=\"Sharawadgi\">sharawadgi</a>, is a <a href=\"/wiki/Musical_perception\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Musical perception\">musical perception</a> or phenomenon regarding <a href=\"/wiki/Timbre\" title=\"Timbre\">timbre</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Texture_(music)\" title=\"Texture (music)\">texture</a> described by Claude Shryer as, \"a sensation of plenitude sometimes created by the contemplation of a complex <a href=\"/wiki/Soundscape\" title=\"Soundscape\">soundscape</a> whose beauty is inexplicable.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> It is important to note that sharawadji is not a stimulus, but rather a reaction to a stimulus.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Musicworks_1998_p._22_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Musicworks_1998_p._22-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> Shryer also elaborated on searching for this, \"state of awareness,\" by the means of, \"one tend[ing] an open ear in the hopes of experiencing the sublime beauty of a given sound in an unexpected context.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The experience of the sharawadji sonic effect is often heavily dictated by personal context as well as the perception of the listener. One striking example of this effect is the appreciation of the sound of rumbling <a href=\"/wiki/Thunder\" title=\"Thunder\">thunder</a>: those who are being directly exposed to the element would be more likely to fear it compared to those who experience the sound while in a safe environment. Simply understood, \"sharawadji sounds belong to everyday life, to a known musical style. They become sharawadji only through decontextualization, through a rupture of meaning.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-Augoyard_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Augoyard-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Origin\">Origin</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sharawadji_effect&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Origin\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Seventeenth-century European travelers originally coined the term as an aesthetic effect that, \"comes about as a surprise and will carry you elsewhere, beyond strict representation \u2014 out of context.\" The term <i>sharawadji</i> was speculated to originate from China and was understood as, \"the beauty that occurs with no discernible order or arrangement\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-Augoyard_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Augoyard-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>\"All of us are searching for that enveloping soundscape that takes us beyond to indescribable realms of beauty, what the Persian philosophers once called the <i>sharawadji effect</i>.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sharawadji_effect&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Auditory_illusion\" title=\"Auditory illusion\">Auditory illusion</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Musique_concr%C3%A8te\" title=\"Musique concr\u00e8te\">Musique concr\u00e8te</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sharawadji_effect&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Waterman, Ellen and Harley, James. \"Open Ears Festival of Music and Sound.\" <i>Computer Music Journal</i> 23.1 (1999): 79-82. Web.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Musicworks_1998_p._22-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Musicworks_1998_p._22_2-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://books.google.com/books?id=zMY4AQAAIAAJ\"><i>Musicworks</i></a>. Music Gallery. 1998. pp.&#160;22 ff<span class=\"reference-accessdate\">. Retrieved <span class=\"nowrap\">13 September</span> 2018</span>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Musicworks&amp;rft.pages=22+ff.&amp;rft.pub=Music+Gallery&amp;rft.date=1998&amp;rft_id=https%3A%2F%2Fbooks.google.com%2Fbooks%3Fid%3DzMY4AQAAIAAJ&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ASharawadji+effect\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Ulvaeus, edited by <a href=\"/wiki/David_Rothenberg\" title=\"David Rothenberg\">David Rothenberg</a> &amp; Marta (2009). <i>The Book of Music and Nature: An Anthology of Sounds, Words, Thoughts</i> (Second edition. ed.). Middletown, Conn.: Wesleyan University Press. pp. 125. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780819569356\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9780819569356\">9780819569356</a>.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Augoyard-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-ba